    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-05-29T11:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-05-29T11:00:00-05:00" n="1003"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1003">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">822.00/1659: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Ecuador</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Scotten</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Quito</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-05-29T11:00:00-05:00"
                            >May 29, 1944—11 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 2:02 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>516. Following from Williamson<note n="1" xml:id="d1003fn1">Harold L. Williamson,
                        Consul General at Guayaquil.</note> received through private Panagra<note
                        n="2" xml:id="d1003fn2">Pan American Grace Airways.</note> wire: <quote
                        rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“US Urgent May 29, 9 a.m. Revolution broke out in Guayaquil about 10 last
                            night. While facts not yet clear apparently was engineered by Captain
                            Girón of the Battalion General Villamil. Army conscripts distributed
                            arms to populace who after disposing of secret police proceed[ed] to
                            engage <hi rend="italic">carabineros</hi>. Army and navy personnel
                            joined insurgent movement as well as numerous lower ranking officers.
                            Higher army officers meanwhile imprisoned by revolutionists. After all
                            night battle with formidable machine gun, rifle and other fire and
                            presumably heavy casualties revolutionists appear to be in entire
                            control of city and except for isolated resistance to have subdued <hi
                                rend="italic">carabineros</hi>. Light firing still continues.
                            Governor is reported besieged in his residence. Revolution would appear
                            to be of Velasco<note n="3" xml:id="d1003fn3">José María Velasco Ibarra,
                                ex-President of Ecuador, in exile in Colombia; presidential
                                candidate of a coalition of opposition parties known as the Alianza
                                Democrática Ecuatoriana, which overthrew the Government.</note>
                            origin and also is said to be a protest against alleged oppression of
                            Government.”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Scotten</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
